properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions, with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow, are expected to persist in Ulukhaktok today and tonight. Conditions will improve through the day Saturday as snowfall tapers and wind speeds begin to ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NTStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-23T09:26:03-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-11-22T17:27:03-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0703150191.2019
Area: Ulukhaktok
properties.Author: Environment Canada

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow at times heavy is expected over the Highlands of Inverness County on Saturday, starting in the morning and persisting into Saturday night. Accumulations of up to 25 centimetres are expected. Wet snow is expected over lower elevations of Inverness County. However, accumulations are expected to be much lower, in the 5 to 10 centimetre range, due to the fact that temperatures are forecast to remain slightly above freezing. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-23T12:23:15-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-11-22T20:24:15-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.4202894275.2019
Area: Inverness County - Mabou and north

properties.Title: Wreckhouse Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds are expected or occurring. Peak wind gusts: 120 km/h. Time frame: Saturday morning. Remarks: Southeasterly winds will begin to strengthen overnight with gusts up to 80 km/h. Winds will further strengthen Saturday morning before shifting to the southwest and diminishing near noon. ### Wreckhouse wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. properties.Title: Update: High Water Advisory Alert Is Being Issued For The Roseau River From Gardenton To Stuartburn
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre has issued a High Water Advisory for the Roseau River from Gardenton to Stuartburn due to expected high flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-11-23T11:30:00-06:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-11-22T11:45:07-06:00, 73D1D33D-C50C-81E6-7C60-3E6661AED930
Area: Roseau River from Gardenton to Stuartburn
properties.Author: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm is expected. Heavy snowfall beginning Friday night over Clyde River and tapering off Saturday evening. A low pressure system is currently giving snow to Clyde River. The intensity of the snowfall will increase throughout the night, with the heaviest snow falling between midnight and noon. Heavy snowfall will taper off toward Saturday evening. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: northeasterly up to 100 km/h. Locations: Exposed coastal areas of the Bonavista and Bay de Verde Peninsulas. Time span: gusts will drop below 100 km/h this afternoon, though gusts to 80 km/h will persist until this evening. ### Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
